  "texts": [
    "We will start from the uncontrolled model and then move on to the controlled one.",
    "In particular, we will show that the latter prevents the creation of agents with extremely high or low levels of activity (matching our second goal explained at the beginning of Section 3).In Subsection 4.2, we then move on to analyze the evolution of opinions alone, both interactions agent-agent and agent-leader are taken into account and all agents have become active.",
    "In particular, we will prove that the marginal of f (t, A, w) in w converges toward a global equilibrium state (a Beta-type distribution) of the corresponding reduced model, when t → +∞.",
    "Our analysis makes use of relative entropy techniques inspired from [2,19] and extended in a novel way to deal with Fokker-Planck equations that involve nonconstant time-dependent coefficients.Finally, in Subsection 4.3 we will derive some relevant analytical properties of the whole distribution f (t, A, w), notably its nonnegativity, its L ∞ (R +, L 1 (R × I)) regularity, and its uniqueness in a specific linearized setting.",
    "Evolution of the social activity of individuals."
